# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: american-chemical-society
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c) organization** is a nonprofit organization in the federal law of the United States according to Internal Revenue Code (26 U.S.C. § 501(c)).
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Such organizations are exempt from some federal income taxes.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Sections 503 through 505 set out the requirements for obtaining such exemptions.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Many states refer to Section 501(c) for definitions of organizations exempt from state taxation as well.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from individuals, corporations, and unions.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] For example, a nonprofit organization may be tax-exempt under section 501(c)(3) if its primary activities are charitable, religious, educational, scientific, literary, testing for public safety, fostering amateur sports competition, or preventing cruelty to children or animals.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] According to the IRS Publication 557, in the *Organization Reference Chart* section, the following is an exact list of 501(c) organization types (29 in total) and their corresponding descriptions.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c) organization is subject to tax on its unrelated business income.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] For most organizations, an organization's activity generates unrelated business income if it is regularly carried on and it is not substantially related to furthering the exempt purpose of the organization.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Disposal of donated goods valued over $2,500, or acceptance of goods worth over $5,000 may trigger special filing and record-keeping requirements.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c) organization must maintain proper records and file certain annual or special-purpose tax returns, e.g., 26 U.S.C. § 6033 and 26 U.S.C. § 6050L.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Prior to 2008, an annual return was not generally required from an exempt organization with less than $25,000 in gross income yearly.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Since 2008, most organizations whose annual gross receipts are less than $50,000 must file an annual information return known as Form 990-N.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Form 990-N, Form 990, Form 990-EZ, and Form 990-PF must be submitted electronically.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Failure to file required returns such as Form 990 (Return of Organization Exempt From Income Tax) may result in fines of up to $250,000 per year.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Exempt or political organizations, excluding churches or similar religious entities, must make their returns, reports, notices, and exempt applications available for public inspection.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Form 4506-A also allows the public inspection or photocopying access to Form 1023 "Application for Recognition of Exemption" or Form 1024, Form 8871 "Political Organization Notice of Section 527 Status", and Form 8872 "Political Organization Report of Contribution and Expenditures".
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Internet access to many organizations' 990 and some other forms are available through GuideStar.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Failure to file such timely returns and to make other specific information available to the public also is prohibited.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Between 2010 and 2017 the IRS revoked the nonprofit status of more than 760,000 nonprofit organizations for failing to file the 990 form.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The 501(c)(3) exemption also applies for any unincorporated community chest, fund, cooperating association, or foundation that is organized and operated exclusively for those purposes.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] There are also supporting organizations—often referred to in shorthand form as "Friends of" organizations.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] 26 U.S.C. § 170, provides a deduction, for federal income tax purposes, for some donors who make charitable contributions to most types of 501(c)(3) organizations, among others.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Organizations described in section 501(c)(3) are prohibited from conducting political campaign activities to intervene in elections to public office.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] On the other hand, public charities (but not private foundations) may conduct a limited amount of lobbying to influence legislation.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Although the law states that "No substantial part..." of a public charity's activities can go to lobbying, charities may register for a 501(h) election allowing them to lawfully conduct lobbying activities as long as their financial expenditure does not exceed a specified amount.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c)(3) organizations risk loss of tax exempt status if any of these rules are violated.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(3) organization is allowed to conduct some or all of its charitable activities outside the United States.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Donors' contributions to a 501(c)(3) organization are tax-deductible only if the contribution is for the use of the 501(c)(3) organization, and that the 501(c)(3) organization is not merely serving as an agent or conduit of a foreign charitable organization.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(4) organization** is a social welfare organization, such as a civic organization or a neighborhood association.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] An organization is considered by the IRS to be operated exclusively for the promotion of social welfare if it is primarily engaged in promoting the common good and general welfare of the people of the community.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Net earnings must be exclusively used for charitable, educational, or recreational purposes.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c)(4)s are similar to 501(c)(5)s and 501(c)(6)s in that the organizations may inform the public on controversial subjects and attempt to influence legislation relevant to its program.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Unlike 501(c)(3) organizations, they may also participate in political campaigns and elections, as long as their primary activity is the promotion of social welfare and related to the organization's purpose.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The income tax exemption for 501(c)(4) organizations applies to most of their operations, but income spent on political activities—generally the advocacy of a particular candidate in an election—is taxable.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] An "action" organization generally qualifies as a 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] An "action" organization is one whose activities substantially include, or are exclusively, direct or grassroots lobbying related to advocacy for or against legislation or proposing, supporting, or opposing legislation that is related to its purpose.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(4) organization may directly or indirectly support or oppose a candidate for public office as long as such activities are not a substantial amount of its activities.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(4) organization that lobbies must register with the Clerk of the House if it lobbies members of the House or their staff.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Likewise, a 501(c)(4) organization must register with the Secretary of the Senate if it lobbies members of the Senate or their staff.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] In addition, the 501(c)(4) organization must either inform its members the amount it spends on lobbying or pay a proxy tax to the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Lobbying expenses and political expenses are not deductible as business expenses.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Wisconsin Right to Life, Inc.*, in which the Supreme Court struck down the part of the McCain-Feingold Act that prohibited 501(c)(4)s, 501(c)(5)s, and 501(c)(6)s from broadcasting electioneering communications.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The Act defined an electioneering communication as a communication that mentions a candidate's name 60 days before a primary or 30 days before a general election.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations are not tax-deductible as charitable donations unless the organization is either a volunteer fire department or a veterans organization.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Dues or contributions to 501(c)(4) organizations may be deductible as a business expense under IRC 162, although amounts paid for intervention or participation in any political campaign, direct lobbying, grass roots lobbying, and contact with certain federal officials are not deductible.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] If a 501(c)(4) engages in a substantial number of these activities, then only the amount of dues or contributions that can be attributed to other activities may be deductible as a business expense.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The organization must provide a notice to its members containing a reasonable estimate of the amount related to lobbying and political campaign expenditures, or else it is subject to a proxy tax on its lobbying and political campaign expenditures.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] It must also state that contributions to the organization are not deductible as charitable contributions during fundraising.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to disclose their donors publicly, with the exception of organizations that make independent expenditures as of 2018.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The former complete lack of disclosure led to extensive use of the 501(c)(4) provisions for organizations that are actively involved in lobbying, and has become controversial.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Criticized as "dark money", spending from these organizations on political advertisements has exceeded spending from Super PACs.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Spending by organizations that do not disclose their donors increased from less than $5.2 million in 2006 to well over $300 million during the 2012 election season.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The origins of 501(c)(4) organizations date back to the Revenue Act of 1913, which created a new group of tax-exempt organizations dedicated to social welfare in a precursor to what is now Internal Revenue Code Section 501(c)(4).
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The Protecting Americans from Tax Hikes Act of 2015 introduced a new requirement on 501(c)(4) organizations.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Within 60 days of the organization's formation, a 501(c)(4) organization is required to file Form 8976 with the Internal Revenue Service as notification that it is operating as a section 501(c)(4) organization.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The Internal Revenue Service will acknowledge receipt of the notification, but the acknowledgment is not a determination that the organization qualifies for section 501(c)(4) tax-exempt status.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(4) organization is not required to send the notification if the organization was formed on or before July 8, 2016, and it either applied for a determination letter using Form 1024 or filed a Form 990 between December 19, 2015, and July 8, 2016.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] As of January 2018, the application for recognition of exemption as a 501(c)(4) organization is a new form, Form 1024-A, rather than Form 1024.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] In 2017 revocations of 501(c)(4) groups comprised 58% which usually is only 15% of the total nonprofits which have their tax status revoked by the IRS for their failure to file Form 990.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(5) organization** is a labor organization, an agricultural organization, or a horticultural organization.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Labor unions, county fairs, and flower societies are examples of these types of groups.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Labor union organizations were a primary benefactor of this organization type, dating to the 19th century.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] According to the Internal Revenue Service, a 501(c)(5) organization has a duty of providing service to its members first.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The organization's benefits may not inure to a specific member, but the rules for inurement vary among the three different types of organizations under this segment.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(5) organization can make unlimited corporate, individual, or union contributions.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A labor organization may pay benefits to its members because paying benefits improves all members' shared working conditions.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] An agricultural organization can provide financial assistance to its members in order to improve the conditions of those engaged in agricultural pursuits generally.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Members can benefit in incidental ways from the organization's exempt activities as long as the benefits are available to all persons.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The first exemption for labor organizations from corporate income tax was enacted as part of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The Revenue Act of 1913 excluded "labor, agricultural, or horticultural organizations" from income tax liability.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(6) organizations, 501(c)(5) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c)(5) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common union interests of its members.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c)(5) organizations can receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of noncash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A union membership dues paid to a 501(c)(5) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(5) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The Federal Election Commission is required to enforce this provision based on a federal court decision in 2018.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(6) organization** is a business league, a chamber of commerce like the U.S.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A business league may qualify if it is an association of persons having a common business interest, whose purpose is to promote the common business interest and whose activities improve business conditions rather than actually conduct the business itself.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Members of the organization must be of the same trade, business, occupation, or profession in order to qualify.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A local chamber of commerce or board of trade could qualify for similar reasons except that they may promote the common economic interests of all the commercial enterprises in a given trade or community.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] In order to qualify for a tax-exemption under section 501(c)(6), the organization must specify that it seeks to promote and improve business condition for a specific type of business.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Improving business conditions for *all* types of businesses is not generally qualifying.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Similarly, providing a service for a specific type of business is also not typically qualifying, as that would usually be more of a commercial enterprise.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] For example, the service of managing health insurance plans for its member businesses is often a commercial enterprise if it is not substantially related to improving the business conditions for specific lines of businesses.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] An association that promotes the common interests of certain hobbyists would not qualify because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider hobbies to be activities conducted as businesses.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] An organization whose primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members does not qualify because the organization is performing a service for its members rather than promoting common interests.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] If an organization's primary activity is advertising the products or services of its members' industry as a whole, however, the organization will generally qualify if it also performs other services for its members.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Much like 501(c)(4) and 501(c)(5) organizations, 501(c)(6) organizations may also perform some political activities.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c)(6) organizations are allowed to attempt to influence legislation that is related to the common business interests of its members.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(6) organization may receive unlimited contributions from corporations, individuals, and labor unions.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The names and addresses of contributors are not required to be made available for public inspection, with the exception of a 501(c)(6) organization that makes independent expenditures.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] All other information, including the amount of contributions, the description of non-cash contributions, and any other information, is required to be made available for public inspection unless it clearly identifies the contributor.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Chamber of Commerce is a large political spender, and Freedom Partners used its status as a 501(c)(6) organization to raise and distribute over $250 million during the 2012 election campaigns without disclosing its donors.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The group's existence was not publicly known until nearly a year after the election.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A business's membership dues paid to a 501(c)(6) organization are generally an ordinary and necessary business expense.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The membership dues are tax-deductible in full unless a substantial part of the 501(c)(6) organization's activities consists of political activity, in which case a tax deduction is allowed only for the portion of membership dues that are for other activities.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The predecessor of IRC 501(c)(6) was enacted as part of the Revenue Act of 1913 likely due to a U.S.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Chamber of Commerce request for an exemption for nonprofit "civic" and "commercial" organizations, which resulted in IRC 501(c)(4) for nonprofit "civic" organizations and IRC 501(c)(6) for nonprofit "commercially-oriented" organizations.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The Revenue Act of 1928 amended the statute to include real estate boards.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] In 1966, professional football leagues were added to the described organizations.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] IRC 501(c)(6) amendment was enacted in 1966 to ensure that a professional football league's exemption would not be jeopardized because it administered a players' pension fund.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Additionally, a professional sports league's exemption is not to be jeopardized because its primary source of revenue is the sale of television broadcasting rights to its games because the broadcasting of games increases public awareness of the sport.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] In 2013, Senator Tom Coburn introduced legislation to disallow a tax exemption for the National Football League, the Professional Golfers' Association of America, and other professional sports organizations.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Coburn estimated the tax exemption cost $100 million, but he said he could not get other members of Congress to support the legislation.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(7) organization** is a social or recreational club that is organized for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Members must share interests and have a common goal directed toward pleasure and recreation, and the organization must provide opportunities for personal contact among members.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The organization's facilities and services must be open to its members and their guests only.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The organization must be a club of individuals, and no individual may derive profit from the organization's net earnings.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Examples include college alumni associations; college fraternities or college sororities operating chapter houses for students; country clubs; amateur sport clubs; supper clubs that provide a meeting place, library, and dining room for members; hobby clubs; and garden clubs.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A substantial amount of the 501(c)(7) organization's activities must be related to social and recreational activities for its members.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] No more than 35 percent of its gross receipts may derive from non-members, and no more than 15 percent of its gross receipts is permitted to come from use of its facilities or services by the general public.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] An organization that exceeds these limits may lose its 501(c)(7) status.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Similarly, if at least 75 percent of a group using club facilities are members of the organization, the Internal Revenue Service will assume the nonmembers are the guests of the member, and the revenue is deemed to be derived from the member.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] It is the responsibility of the organization to maintain these records.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] If the organization does not keep sufficient records to link revenue to a member, the Internal Revenue Service assumes the revenue came from a nonmember.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The organization is subject to Unrelated Business Income Tax for the revenue derived from nonmember use of its facilities and services, less allowable deductions.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] If the organization sells assets that were previously used for recreational or social purposes, the proceeds are considered related business income as long as the proceeds are reinvested in the organization.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Public use of the organization's facilities must be minimal, generally either less than $2,500 per year or less than five percent of its total gross receipts from normal and usual activities of the club.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A 501(c)(7) organization cannot have a written policy of discriminating on the basis of race, color, or religion.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Nevertheless, a 501(c)(7) organization is permitted to limit its members to a particular religion in order to further the teachings of that religion.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] An auxiliary of a 501(c)(8) fraternal benefit society that limits membership to members of a particular religion is allowed to do so as well.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Having written policies that limit its membership by ethnic origin and gender would not jeopardize the organization's tax-exempt status.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Congress justified the tax-exemption with the reasoning that the members join to provide themselves with recreational or social organization without further tax consequences, similar as if they had paid for the benefits directly.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Tax-exemption was available for organizations operated exclusively for pleasure, recreation, and other nonprofitable purposes.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] In 1969, Congress passed a law stating that social and recreational clubs were permitted to engage in some unrelated business income, subject to income tax.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(8) organization** is a fraternal benefit society.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The society must have members of a similar calling, recreation, or profession, or members who work together to accomplish a worthy goal.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The members have associated themselves in order to help each other and to promote the common cause.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The society must have written documentation of its eligibility standards for membership, classes of membership, a process of admission, and rights and privileges of members.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The members must have a common bond, which may be based on religious beliefs, gender, occupation, ethnicity, or shared values.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The society must have a supreme governing body and subordinate lodges into which members are elected, initiated, or admitted in accordance with its laws.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The supreme governing body should be composed of delegates elected directly by members or intermediate assemblies.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The society must offer benefits to members, which may include life insurance, medical insurance, scholarships, educational programs, travel opportunities, and discount programs.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Revenue generated from providing benefits to non-members must be insubstantial to the society and may be taxable as unrelated business income.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Fraternal benefit societies trace their lineage back through mutual benefit societies, friendly societies and eventually to medieval guilds.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Many fraternal benefit societies were founded to serve the needs of immigrants and other under-served groups who shared common bonds of religion, ethnicity, gender, occupation or shared values.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Section 38 of the Payne–Aldrich Tariff Act of 1909 was the first law to provide a tax-exemption for fraternal beneficiary societies.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The tax-exemption was later codified as section 501(c)(8) with the Internal Revenue Code of 1954.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Similar to 501(c)(8) organizations, 501(c)(10) organizations are also fraternal societies, orders, or associations operating under the lodge system, but 501(c)(10) organizations do not offer life, sick, accident, or other benefits.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] 501(c)(10) organizations devote net earnings exclusively to religious, charitable, scientific, literary, educational, and fraternal purposes.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A **501(c)(13)** organization is a certain type of cemetery company.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] There are two primary types of eligible cemetery companies.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A mutual cemetery company must be either "owned by and operated exclusively for the benefit of its lot owners who hold such lots for bona fide burial purposes and not for the purpose of resale" or engages in the burial of impoverished people performing similar charitable activities.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A nonprofit cemetery corporation must be incorporated solely for the purpose of the burial or the cremation of bodies and no part of its net earnings inures to the benefit of any private shareholder or individual.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Any net gain by the cemetery must be devoted to certain cemetery functions, such as the cemetery's operations, maintenance, and improvements; acquisition of cemetery property; and investment of the net gain in order to provide additional income for cemetery functions.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Net gains are not allowed to be distributed to individuals.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A perpetual care fund that is used by a profit-making cemetery to maintain cemetery properties and burial lots is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] On the other hand, a nonprofit organization may have a perpetual care fund without jeopardizing its exemption under Section 501(c)(13).
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A cemetery that owns or operates a morgue, whether on its own grounds or elsewhere, is not eligible under 501(c)(13) because the Internal Revenue Service does not consider mortuary services necessarily incident to burial purposes.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The provision of traditional burial services that directly support and maintain basic tenets and beliefs of a religion regarding burial of its members" may still be eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A cemetery that buries animals is not eligible under 501(c)(13).
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] A cemetery company wishing to be recognized under Section 501(c)(13) needs to prepare and file Form 1024 with the Internal Revenue Service.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Charitable contributions to a 501(c)(13) organization are tax-deductible to the donor.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Payments for perpetual care of a particular lot or a particular crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Payments made as part of the purchase price of a burial lot or crypt are not considered tax-deductible charitable contributions, even if a portion of the payment is for the perpetual care of the entirety of the cemetery.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Bequests or gifts to a 501(c)(13) cemetery are not deductible for federal estate tax purposes or gift tax purposes.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] Historically, cemeteries were exempt from local property taxes and excise taxes in most states because states generally considered cemeteries to be performing a recognized civic service.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] The Tariff Act of 1913 provided an exemption from federal income taxes for mutual cemetery companies that were organized and operated exclusively "for the benefit of their members".
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] In 1921, Congress extended the tax-exemption to cemetery companies that are not mutual and to cemetery companies that are not operated for profit as well as any corporation solely incorporated to operate a cemetery and whose net gains do not inure to any person.
[src:american-chemical-society/501-c-organization] In 1970, Congress added crematorium in the definition of cemetery for the purposes of Section 501(c)(13).
[src:american-chemical-society/acs-applied-materials-interfaces] The journal is abstracted and indexed in: CAS, MEDLINE/PubMed, Current Contents, and Science Citation Index Expanded.
[src:american-chemical-society/acs-applied-materials-interfaces] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2023 impact factor of 8.5.
[src:american-chemical-society/acs-applied-nano-materials] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2024 impact factor of 5.5.
[src:american-chemical-society/acs-catalysis] The journal publishes the following types of articles: Letters, Articles, Reviews, Perspectives, and Viewpoints.
[src:american-chemical-society/acs-catalysis] Reviews, Perspectives, and Viewpoints appear mostly on invitation.
[src:american-chemical-society/acs-catalysis] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2023 impact factor of 11.3.
[src:american-chemical-society/acs-central-science] Established in 2015, it is the first fully open-access journal (diamond open access) published by ACS Publications, the American Chemical Society's publishing arm.
[src:american-chemical-society/acs-central-science] According to the *Journal Citation Reports*, the journal has a 2023 impact factor of 12.7.
[src:american-chemical-society/acs-chemical-biology] The journal publishes the following types of articles: research letters, articles, reviews, and perspectives, as well as specially commissioned articles that describe emerging directions in the field of chemical biology.
[src:american-chemical-society/acs-chemical-biology] Letters presenting findings of broad interest are typically five printed pages or fewer, while articles are twelve printed pages or fewer.
[src:american-chemical-society/acs-chemical-biology] Finally, reviews cover key concepts of interest to a broad readership.
[src:american-chemical-society/acs-chemical-biology] The journal has published the first three-dimensional interactive chemical structures replicating printed journal figures.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The **American Chemical Society** (**ACS**) is a scientific society based in the United States that supports scientific inquiry in the field of chemistry.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Founded in 1876 at New York University, the ACS currently has more than 262,000 members at all degree levels and in all fields of chemistry, chemical engineering, and related fields.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] It is one of the world's largest scientific societies by membership.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS is a 501(c)(3) non-profit organization and holds a congressional charter under Title 36 of the United States Code.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Its headquarters are located in Washington, D.C., and it has a large concentration of staff in Columbus, Ohio.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS is a source of scientific information through its peer-reviewed scientific journals, national conferences, and the Chemical Abstracts Service.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Its publications division produces over 90 scholarly journals including the prestigious *Journal of the American Chemical Society*, as well as the weekly trade magazine *Chemical & Engineering News*.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS holds national meetings twice a year covering the complete field of chemistry and also holds smaller conferences concentrating on specific chemical fields or geographic regions.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The primary source of income of the ACS is the Chemical Abstracts Service, a provider of chemical databases worldwide.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS has student chapters in virtually every major university in the United States and outside the United States as well.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] These student chapters mainly focus on volunteering opportunities, career development, and the discussion of student and faculty research.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The organization also publishes textbooks, administers several national chemistry awards, provides grants for scientific research, and supports various educational and outreach activities.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] In 1874, a group of American chemists gathered at the Joseph Priestley House to mark the 100th anniversary of Priestley's discovery of oxygen.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Two years later, on April 6, 1876, during a meeting of chemists at the University of the City of New York (now New York University) the American Chemical Society was founded.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The society received its charter of incorporation from the State of New York in 1877.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Although Chandler was a likely choice to become the society's first president because of his role in organizing the society, New York University chemistry professor John William Draper was elected as the first president of the society because of his national reputation.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Draper was a photochemist and pioneering photographer who had produced one of the first photographic portraits in 1840.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Chandler would later serve as president in 1881 and 1889.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] In the ACS logo, originally designed in the early 20th century by Tiffany's Jewelers and used since 1909, a stylized symbol of a kaliapparat is used.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The *Journal of the American Chemical Society* was founded in 1879 to publish original chemical research.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] It was the first journal published by ACS and is still the society's flagship peer-reviewed publication.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] In 1907, Chemical Abstracts was established as a separate journal (it previously appeared within JACS), which later became the Chemical Abstracts Service, a division of ACS that provides chemical information to researchers and others worldwide.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] *Chemical & Engineering News* is a weekly trade magazine that has been published by ACS since 1923.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The society adopted a new constitution aimed at nationalizing the organization in 1890.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] In 1905, the American Chemical Society moved from New York City to Washington, D.C.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] ACS was reincorporated under a congressional charter in 1937.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Congress and signed by president Franklin D.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] ACS's headquarters moved to its current location in downtown Washington in 1941.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] ACS first established technical divisions in 1908 to foster the exchange of information among scientists who work in particular fields of chemistry or professional interests.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Divisional activities include organizing technical sessions at ACS meetings, publishing books and resources, administering awards and lectureships, and conducting other events.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The original five divisions were 1) organic chemistry, 2) industrial chemists and chemical engineers, 3) agricultural and food chemistry, 4) fertilizer chemistry, and 5) physical and inorganic chemistry.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] As of 2016, there are 32 technical divisions of ACS.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] This is the largest division of the Society.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] It marked its 100th anniversary in 2008.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The first Chair of the Division was Edward Curtis Franklin.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The Organic Division played a part in establishing Organic Syntheses, Inc. and Organic Reactions, Inc. and it maintains close ties to both organizations.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The symposia also honor national award winners, including the Arthur C.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Cope Award, Cope Scholar Award, James Flack Norris Award in Physical Organic Chemistry, Herbert C.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Brown Award for Creative Research in Synthetic Methods.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The Division helps to organize symposia at the international meeting called Pacifichem and it organizes the biennial National Organic Chemistry Symposium (NOS) which highlights recent advances in organic chemistry and hosts the Roger Adams Award address.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The Division also organizes corporate sponsorships to provide fellowships for PhD students and undergraduates.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] It also organizes the Graduate Research Symposium and manages award and travel grant programs for undergraduates.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Local sections were authorized in 1890 and are autonomous units of the American Chemical Society.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] They elect their own officers and select representatives to the national ACS organization.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Local sections also provide professional development opportunities for members, organize community outreach events, offer awards, and conduct other business.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The Rhode Island Section was the first local section of ACS, organized in 1891.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] There are currently 186 local sections of the American Chemical Society in all 50 states, the District of Columbia, and Puerto Rico.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] International Chemical Sciences Chapters allow ACS members outside of the U.S. to organize locally for professional and scientific exchange.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] There are currently 36 International Chemical Sciences Chapters.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] ACS states that it offers teacher training to support the professional development of science teachers so they can better present chemistry in the classroom, foster the scientific curiosity of our nation's youth and encourage future generations to pursue scientific careers.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] As of 2009, Clifford and Kathryn Hach donated $33 million to ACS, to continue the work of the Hach Scientific Foundation in supporting high school chemistry teaching.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The Society sponsors the United States National Chemistry Olympiad (USNCO), a contest used to select the four-member team that represents the United States at the International Chemistry Olympiad (IChO).
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS Division of Chemical Education provides standardized tests for various subfields of chemistry.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The two most commonly used tests are the undergraduate-level tests for general and organic chemistry.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Each of these tests consists of 70 multiple-choice questions, and gives students 110 minutes to complete the exam.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS also approves certified undergraduate programs in chemistry.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] A student who completes the required laboratory and course work—sometimes in excess of what a particular college may require for its Bachelor's degree—is considered by the Society to be well trained for professional work.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS coordinates two annual public awareness campaigns, National Chemistry Week and Chemists Celebrate Earth Week, as part of its educational outreach.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Since 1978 and 2003 respectively, the campaigns have been celebrated with a yearly theme, such as "Chemistry Colors Our World" (2015) and "Energy: Now and Forever!" (2013).
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The GCI was founded in 1997 as an independent non-profit organization, by chemists Joe Breen and Dennis Hjeresen in cooperation with the Environmental Protection Agency.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The Petroleum Research Fund (PRF) is an endowment fund administered by the ACS that supports advanced education and fundamental research in the petroleum and fossil fuel fields at non-profit institutions.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Several categories of grants are offered for various career levels and institutions.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The fund awarded more than $25 million in grants in 2007.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The PRF traces its origins to the acquisition of the Universal Oil Products laboratory by a consortium of oil companies in 1931.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The companies established a trust fund, The Petroleum Research Fund, in 1944 to prevent antitrust litigation tied to their UOP assets.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS was named the beneficiary of the trust.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The first grants from the PRF were awarded in 1954.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] In 2000, the trust was transferred to the ACS.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS established The American Chemical Society Petroleum Research Fund and the previous trust was dissolved.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The PRF trust was valued at $144.7 million in December 2014.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS International Activities is the birthplace of the ACS International Center, an online resource for scientists and engineers looking to study abroad or explore an international career or internship.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The site houses information on hundreds of scholarships and grants related to all levels of experience to promote scientific mobility of researchers and practitioners in STEM fields.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The Society grants membership to undergraduates as student members provided they can pay the $25 yearly dues.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Any university may start its own ACS Student Chapter and receive benefits of undergraduate participation in regional conferences and discounts on ACS publications.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The American Chemical Society administers 64 national awards, medals and prizes based on scientific contributions at various career levels that promote achievement across the chemical sciences.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS national awards program began in 1922 with the establishment of the Priestley Medal, the highest award offered by the ACS, which is given for distinguished services to chemistry.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Additional awards are offered by divisions, local sections and other bodies of ACS.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Nichols Medal Award was the first ACS award to honor outstanding researchers in the field of chemistry.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] It was established in 1903 by the ACS New York Section and is named for William H.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Nichols, an American chemist and businessman and one of the original founders of ACS.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Of the over 100 Nichols Medalists, 16 have subsequently been awarded the Nobel Prize in Chemistry.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The Willard Gibbs Award, granted by the ACS Chicago Section, was established in 1910 in honor of Josiah Willard Gibbs, the Yale University professor who formulated the phase rule.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The Georgia Local Section of ACS has awarded the Herty Medal since 1933 recognizing outstanding chemists who have significantly contributed to their chosen fields.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] All chemists in academic, government, or industrial laboratories who have been residing in the southeastern United States for at least 10 years are eligible.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The New York Section of ACS also gives Leadership Awards.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The Leadership Awards are the highest honors given by the Chemical Marketing and Economic Group of ACS NY since December 6, 2012.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] They are presented to leaders of industry, investments, and other sectors, for their contributions to science, technology, engineering and mathematics (STEM) initiatives.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Roy Vagelos (Regeneron, Merck), Thomas M.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Connelly (DuPont) and Juan Pablo del Valle (Mexichem).
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS also administers regional awards presented annually at regional meetings.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Ann Nalley Regional Award for Volunteer Service to the American Chemical Society, Regional Awards for Excellence in High School Teaching, and the Stanley C.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] Israel Regional Award for Advancing Diversity in the Chemical Sciences.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] ACS Publications is the publishing division of the ACS.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] It is a nonprofit academic publisher of scientific journals covering various fields of chemistry and related sciences.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] In addition to academic journals, ACS Publications also publishes *Chemical & Engineering News*, a weekly trade magazine covering news in the chemical profession, *inChemistry*, a magazine for undergraduate students, and *ChemMatters*, a magazine for high school students and teachers.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] However it has recently launched new open access journals and provided authors with open access publishing options.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] In 2006, Congress debated legislation that would have instructed the National Institutes of Health (NIH) to require all investigators it funded to submit copies of final, peer-reviewed journal articles to PubMed Central, a free-access digital repository it operates, within 12 months of publication.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] At the time the American Association of Publishers (of which ACS is a member) hired a public relations firm to counter the open access movement.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] In spite of publishers' opposition, the PubMed Central legislation was passed in December 2007 and became effective in 2008.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] As the open access issue has continued to evolve, so too has the ACS's position.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS has also introduced several open access publishing options for its journals, including providing authors the option to pay an upfront fee to enable free online access to their articles.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] In 2015, the ACS launched the first fully open access journal in the society's history, *ACS Central Science*.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS states that the journal offers the same peer-review standards as its subscription journals, but without publishing charges to either authors or readers.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] A second open access title, *ACS Omega*, an interdisciplinary mega journal, launched in 2016.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] In 2005, the ACS was criticized for opposing the creation of PubChem, which is an open access chemical database developed by the NIH's National Center for Biotechnology Information.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS raised concerns that the publicly supported PubChem database would duplicate and unfairly compete with their existing fee-based Chemical Abstracts Service and argued that the database should only present data created by the Molecular Libraries Screening Center initiative of the NIH.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS lobbied members of the United States Congress to rein in PubChem and hired outside lobbying firms to try to persuade congressional members, the NIH, and the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) against establishing a publicly funded database.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS was unsuccessful, and as of 2012 PubChem is the world's largest free chemical database.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS is also the only provider of a major scientific publication database (SciFinder) that imposes a restriction on the number of records that can be exported.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] None of the competing products, such as Web of Science (owned by Clarivate), Scopus (owned by Elsevier) and The Lens (owned by Cambia) have similar restrictions.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS has been involved in numerous lawsuits regarding access to its databases, trademark rights, and copyrighted material.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] In many of these cases, the ACS lost or ended up with an unenforceable judgement.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS was also found guilty in several lawsuits brought against the Society by its employees.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] In 2004, a group of ACS members criticized the compensation of former executive director and chief executive officer John Crum, whose total salary, expenses, and bonuses for 2002 was reported to be $767,834.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] The ACS defended the figure, saying that it was in line with that of comparable organizations, including for-profit publishers.
[src:american-chemical-society/american-chemical-society] As of 2016, two employees were reported to have a total compensation exceeding $900,000, while 694 had a compensation exceeding $100,000.
